{{icelandic name|Kristinn}} {{Infobox person | name = Kristinn Hrafnsson | image = Wikileaks Spokesperson Kristinn Hrafnsson speaks at the Queensland College of Art, Griffith University, Southbank, Brisbane, Australia 110623.jpg | alt = | caption = Kristinn Hrafnsson speaks in [[Brisbane, Australia]] in June 2011. | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|6|25|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Wikileaks-Sprecher Kristinn Hrafnsson: 'Wir hatten einen Notfallplan' |author=Louise Osborne |url=http://www.taz.de/!62620/ |newspaper=[[Die Tageszeitung]] |location=Berlin |date=10 December 2010 |language=German |trans-title=Wikileaks spokesman Kristinn Hrafnsson: 'We had a contingency plan' |accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref> | birth_place = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = former spokesperson for [[WikiLeaks]] | occupation = [[Investigative journalism|investigative journalist]] }} '''Kristinn Hrafnsson''' (born 25 June 1962) is an [[Iceland]]ic investigative journalist known for his former role as spokesperson for the [[WikiLeaks]] organisation between 2010 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.forbes.com/andygreenberg/2010/12/07/meet-the-new-public-face-of-wikileaks-kristinn-hrafnsson/?boxes=techchannellighttop |title=Meet The New Public Face Of WikiLeaks: Kristinn Hrafnsson |author=Andy Greenberg |date=7 December 2010 |publisher=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref>{{update after|2016|10|12}}
He has worked at various newspapers in Iceland and hosted the television programme [[Kompás]] on the Icelandic channel [[Stöð 2]], where he and his team often exposed criminal activity and corruption in high places. In February 2009, while investigating the connection between Iceland's [[Kaupthing Bank]] and [[Robert Tchenguiz]] and [[Vincent Tchenguiz]], the programme was taken off air and Kristinn and his crew were sacked.<ref>{{cite news |title='Vivimos asediados por la Administración de EE.UU.' |author=Victor-M Amela |author2=Ima Sanchiz |author3=Lluis Amiguet |url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/lacontra/20110617/54172383329/vivimos-asediados-por-la-administracion-de-ee-uu.html |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |location=Barcelona |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title='We live under siege by U.S. Government' }}</ref>
Shortly thereafter, Kristinn was hired by [[RÚV]], the Icelandic National Broadcasting Service. In August 2009, he was working on a story about Kaupthing's loan book which had just been published on the WikiLeaks webpage, when the bank got a gag order issued by the Reykjavik sheriff's office, banning RÚV from reporting on the loan book, which could be publicly accessed online via WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kaupþing fékk lögbann á umfjöllun RÚV |author=Hafsteinn Gunnar Hauksson |url=http://www.visir.is/kaupthing-fekk-logbann-a-umfjollun-ruv/article/2009484113562 |newspaper=[[DV (newspaper)|Vísir]] |location=Reykjavík |date=1 August 2009 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |language=Icelandic |trans-title=Kaupþing receives an injunction on the RÚV coverage }}</ref> The prohibition order was withdrawn later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lögbanni aflétt af fréttaflutningi RÚV |author=Jón Hákon Halldórsson |url=http://www.visir.is/logbanni-aflett-af-frettaflutningi-ruv/article/2009755684302 |newspaper=[[DV (newspaper)|Vísir]] |location=Reykjavík |date=4 August 2009 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |language=Icelandic |trans-title=Injunction lifted on news reporting by RÚV }}</ref>
Kristinn was dismissed from RÚV (his contract was not renewed) in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kristinn Hrafnsson rekinn af Ríkisútvarpinu |url=http://www.visir.is/kaupthing-fekk-logbann-a-umfjollun-ruv/article/2009484113562 |newspaper=Pressan |location=Reykjavík |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |language=Icelandic |trans-title=Kristinn Hrafnsson fired by the National Broadcasting Service }}</ref> After this point, he worked as an independent journalist. Beginning in 2010, he collaborated with WikiLeaks, serving as the organisation's spokesman after founder [[Julian Assange]] withdrew from the limelight. He has called the December 2010 attacks on WikiLeaks by [[MasterCard]], [[Visa Inc.|Visa]], and others a "[[privatisation]] of [[censorship]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icelandreview.com/icelandreview/daily_news/?cat_id=16568&ew_0_a_id=371330 |title=WikiLeaks Rep in Iceland Requests Government Support |date=13 December 2010 |publisher=Iceland Review |accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref> In 2012, in his capacity as WikiLeaks spokesman, he defended the organisation on the website of Swedish Television against what he described as a [[smear campaign]] by the Swedish tabloid [[Expressen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogg.svt.se/debatt/2012/03/05/wikileaks-vi-tanker-inte-smutskasta-sverige/ |title=Wikileaks: Vi tänker inte smutskasta Sverige |work=Debatt |date=5 March 2012 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |trans-title=WikiLeaks: We do not intend to denigrate Sweden |language=Swedish |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614202232/http://blogg.svt.se/debatt/2012/03/05/wikileaks-vi-tanker-inte-smutskasta-sverige/ |archivedate=14 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
Kristinn has been named Icelandic journalist of the year three times, in 2004, 2007 and 2010 by Iceland's National Union of Journalists.<ref>{{cite news |title=WikiLeaks spokesman wins Journalist of the Year in Iceland |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20110304/world-news/wikileaks-spokesman-wins-journalist-of-the-year-in-iceland.353072 |agency=AFP |newspaper=[[The Times (Malta)|The Times]] |location=Valletta, Malta |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref>
In early 2017, Hrafnsson stated that he was no longer spokesperson for Wikileaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movietvtechgeeks.com/wikileaks-loses-spokesman-leaving-julian-assange-alone/|title=Wikileaks loses spokesman leaving Julian Assange alone facing eviction|last=Lang|first=Jeffrey|date=|website=1 Mar 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809045753/https://movietvtechgeeks.com/wikileaks-loses-spokesman-leaving-julian-assange-alone/|archive-date=9 Aug 2017|dead-url=yes|access-date=27 Sep 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://grapevine.is/news/2017/01/18/former-wikileaks-spokesperson-on-manning-sentence-commute-victory-for-justice/ Former Wikileaks Spokesperson On Manning Sentence Commute: "Victory For Justice"]</ref>
Kristinn Hrafnsson was appointed editor in chief of Wikileaks on 26 September 2018 taking over from [[Julian Assange]] <ref>https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/1045034219939016704</ref>
